[4] UK update
Date: Fri 30 Nov 2012
Source: AHVLA [UK Animal Health and Veterinary Laboratories Agency] News Release [summarised, edited]
http://www.defra.gov.uk/ahvla/files/SBV-statistics-301112-2.pdf


Schmallenberg Virus - updated testing results [figures correct as of 30 Nov 2012]
-----------------------------------------------
1. Cattle:
Total number of SBV-affected cattle holdings:
57 with fetal malformations, 373 positive serology, 23 acute clinical disease.
Total 453 infected cattle holdings.

2. Sheep
Total number of SBV-affected sheep holdings:
224 with fetal malformations, 38 positive serology.
Total 262 infected sheep holdings.

3. Grand total (SBV-affected cattle and sheep holdings): 715 holdings.

--
Communicated by:
Gert van der Hoek
Senior Moderator FluTrackers.com

[For the full AHLVA update, including location names, please refer to the source URL.

Recent French SBV data and map, as of 27 Nov 2012, are available at http://www.survepi.org/cerepi/images/documents/surveillance%20sbv%20congnital_traitement%201.pdf. Interestingly, some sheep flocks have reportedly suffered a disease event with short duration which resembled the earlier observations in cattle, namely fever, diarrhea, and milk production drop.

The possibility of SBV spread by internationally traded breeding cattle, underlined by Russia's Rosselkhoznadzor (item 1), deserves to be studied and addressed.

With declining temperatures, the vector season, accompanied by new infections, is expected to be terminated during the coming weeks. - Mod.AS

A ProMED-mail HealthMap for Russia can be found at http://healthmap.org/r/1z-D,
